Description: NBE’s nanoTach® technology comes from proprietary formulation and procedures for making uniform pastes of nanoscale silver powders.
Headquarters Regions: East Coast, Southern US
Full Description: NBE was founded on February 10th, 2005 and owns the exclusive right to use and sell the nanoTach® product in all markets. The licensed technology was developed based on research efforts done by NBE's founder at Virginia Tech. NBE has a high-volume production facility at the Virginia Tech Corporate Research Center in Blacksburg, Virginia. The innovation of NBE’s nanoTach® technology comes from proprietary formulation and procedures for making uniform pastes of nanoscale silver powders. In recent years, a low-temperature joining technique (LTJT) based on silver sintering has emerged as a promising lead-free die-attach solution to replace soldering or epoxy curing. However, the LTJT process with existing micron-scale silver pastes requires a force in excess of 300 Kg on a 1 cm x 1 cm chip to lower the silver sintering temperature. Using NBE’s nanoTach® pastes that can be sintered at low temperature without pressure, the LTJT process is significantly simplified. The nanoTach® technology was recognized with a 2007 R&D 100 Award — a mark of excellence known to industry, government, and academia as proof that the product is one of the most innovative ideas of the year.
Industry Groups: Information Technology, Manufacturing, Science and Engineering
Top 5 Investors: National Science Foundation, Virginia Venture Partners

Full Description: DinnerStar is an end-to-end mobile-based technology company connecting local restaurants and consumers through a Meal Marketplace and a suite of automated patent-pending tools to simplify Takeout, Curbside and Pickup Slotting.   The DinnerStar experience provides the restaurant with a variety of low-cost geo-and time-targeted selling solutions for the high-demand dinner daypart and takeout channel. Available in Android and IOS, the app is rolling out in a beta launch in the Portland-OR area December 2020, with expansion in process now. The app features a number of unique functions that allow consumers and restaurants to decrease reliance on restaurant delivery services ("RDS") and better navigate transactions through a more-informed, precise and entertaining takeout experience. DinnerStar Key Benefits and Functions Include: * Independent restaurants only, by invitation only, for curbside only * Restaurant-focused delivery of unique maker and meal stories * Efficient serve - 3-5 signature items/specials, varies often, presented visually * Choosing signature items unlocks broader restaurant menu * Low cost model; restaurants and consumers benefit substantially * Complete meals with sides included for reduced complexity * Web-based, five-minute self-directed edits for all restaurant details * "Fast-casual " pricing, $8-$15 target range for high volume * Enhanced notifications for reduced consumer and restaurant frustration * DinnerStar "Beacon" signals location and reduces confusion at pickup point * Takeout only - no strangers handling food * No fees to consumers * Flexibility of menu promotion reduces waste and increases profit DinnerStar aims to enable independent restaurants to operate with greater profitability through a more-perfected takeout process. Reducing reliance on delivery services allows restaurants to grow their relationship with customers and keep more profits in-house and in-town.
